{{Campaignbox Korean Cold War}}
The '''Korean Demilitarized Zone''' ('''DMZ'''; [[Hangul|Chosŏn'gŭl/Hangul]]: 한반도 비무장 지대; [[Hanja]]: 韓半島非武裝地帶) is a strip of land running across the [[Korean Peninsula]]. It is established by the provisions of the [[Korean Armistice Agreement]] to serve as a [[buffer zone]] between [[North Korea]] and [[South Korea]]. The [[demilitarized zone]] (DMZ) is a [[border barrier]] that divides the Korean Peninsula roughly in half. It was created by agreement between North Korea, [[China]] and the [[United Nations]] in 1953. The DMZ is {{convert|250|km|mi|abbr=off}} long, and about {{convert|4|km|mi|abbr=off}} wide.

Within the DMZ is a meeting point between the two nations in the small [[Joint Security Area]] (JSA) near the western end of the zone, where negotiations take place. There have been various incidents in and around the DMZ, with military and civilian casualties on both sides. 
{{TOC limit|3}}

==Location==
The Korean Demilitarized Zone intersects but does not follow the [[38th parallel north]], which was the border before the [[Korean War]]. It crosses the parallel on an angle, with the west end of the DMZ lying south of the parallel and the east end lying north of it.
[[File:Korea at night.png|thumb|right|The Korean Demilitarized Zone is visible at night from space]]
The DMZ is {{convert|250|km|mi|abbr=off}} long,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/IOTD/view.php?id=3660 |title=Korean Demilitarized Zone: Image of the Day |publisher=NASA Earth Observatory |accessdate=2010-03-26 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100316031349/http://earthobservatory.nasa.gov/IOTD/view.php?id=3660 |archivedate=16 March 2010 }}</ref> approximately {{convert|4|km|mi|abbr=on}} wide. Though the zone separating both sides is demilitarized, the border beyond that strip is one of the most heavily [[Militarization|militarized]] borders in the world.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2011/06/24/the-worlds-most-dangerous-borders/ |title=The world's most dangerous borders |first=Philip |last=Walker |publisher=Foreign Policy |date=24 June 2011 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170308153821/http://foreignpolicy.com/2011/06/24/the-worlds-most-dangerous-borders/ |archivedate=8 March 2017 }}</ref> The [[Northern Limit Line]], or NLL, is the disputed maritime [[demarcation line]] between North and South Korea in the [[Yellow Sea]], not agreed in the armistice. The coastline and islands on both sides of the NLL are also heavily militarized.<ref>Elferink, Alex G. Oude. (1994). {{Google books|x-VYb-wida8C|''The Law of Maritime Boundary Delimitation: a Case Study of the Russian Federation''|page=314}}</ref>

==History==
[[File:Korea demilitarized zone map - 1969.jpg|thumb|upright=1.4|Detail of the DMZ]]
[[File:KPA3-2a.jpg|thumb|A portion of the North Korean DMZ seen from the [[Joint Security Area]] in January 1976]]
{{main|Division of Korea}}
The [[38th parallel north]]—which divides the Korean Peninsula roughly in half—was the original boundary between the United States and Soviet Union's brief administration areas of Korea at the end of [[World War II]]. Upon the creation of the [[Democratic People's Republic of Korea]] (DPRK, informally "North Korea") and the [[Republic of Korea]] (ROK, informally "South Korea") in 1948, it became a ''[[de facto]]'' international border and one of the most tense fronts in the [[Cold War]].

Both the North and the South remained dependent on their sponsor states from 1948 to the outbreak of the [[Korean War]]. That conflict, which claimed over three million lives and divided the Korean Peninsula along ideological lines, commenced on 25 June 1950, with a full-front DPRK invasion across the 38th parallel, and ended in 1953 after international intervention pushed the [[Front (military)|front]] of the war back to near the 38th parallel.

In the [[Korean Armistice Agreement|Armistice Agreement]] of 27 July 1953, the DMZ was created as each side agreed to move their troops back {{convert|2000|m|mi|abbr=in}} from the front line, creating a buffer zone {{convert|4|km|mi|abbr=on}} wide. The [[Military Demarcation Line]] (MDL) goes through the center of the DMZ and indicates where the front was when the agreement was signed.

Owing to this theoretical [[stalemate]], and genuine hostility between the North and the South, large numbers of troops are stationed along both sides of the line, each side guarding against potential aggression from the other side, even {{Age|1953|July|27}} years after its establishment. The armistice agreement explains exactly how many military personnel and what kind of weapons are allowed in the DMZ. Soldiers from both sides may patrol inside the DMZ, but they may not cross the MDL. However, heavily armed ROK soldiers patrol under the aegis of [[military police]], and have memorized each line of the armistice.<ref name="On Patrol in the DMZ">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/mar/21/north-korea-south-korea-dmz-landmines |title=On patrol in the DMZ: North Korean landmines, biting winds and tin cans:  As tensions on the peninsula escalate, a former South Korean guard describes life at one of the world's most fortified borders. NK News reports |publisher=The Guardian |date=2016-03-21 |accessdate=2016-04-18 |author=Ahn, JH |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416132851/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/mar/21/north-korea-south-korea-dmz-landmines |archivedate=16 April 2016 }}</ref>  [[List of border incidents involving North and South Korea|Sporadic outbreaks of violence]] have killed over 500 South Korean soldiers, 50 US soldiers and 250 soldiers from DPRK along the DMZ between 1953 and 1999.<ref>{{cite web|last=Potts |first=Rolf |title=Korea's no-man's-land |url=http://www.salon.com/1999/02/03/feature_115/ |publisher=Salon |accessdate=31 January 2013 |date=3 February 1999 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130215050040/http://www.salon.com/1999/02/03/feature_115/ |archivedate=15 February 2013 }}</ref>

[[Daeseong-dong]] (also written ''Tae Sung Dong'') and [[Kijong-dong|Kijŏng-dong]] (also known as the "Peace Village") are the only settlements allowed by the armistice committee to remain within the boundaries of the DMZ.<ref name="Tae">{{cite news|url=http://www.stripes.com/article.asp?section=104&article=52586 |title=DMZ sixth-graders become graduates |publisher=''[[Stars and Stripes (newspaper)|Stars and Stripes]]'' |date=2008-02-19 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090611232350/http://www.stripes.com/article.asp?section=104&article=52586 |archivedate=11 June 2009 }}</ref> Residents of Tae Sung Dong are governed and protected by the [[United Nations Command]] and are generally required to spend at least 240 nights per year in the village to maintain their residency.<ref name = "Tae"/> In 2008, the village had a population of 218 people.<ref name = "Tae"/> The villagers of Tae Sung Dong are direct descendants of people who owned the land before the 1950–53 Korean War.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.army.mil/-news/2009/01/26/16093-santa-mobbed-by-students-during-visit-to-joint-security-area/ |title=Santa mobbed by students during visit to Joint Security Area |publisher=army.mil.com -The Official U.S. Army Website |accessdate=2009-12-11 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091124043626/http://www.army.mil/-news/2009/01/26/16093-santa-mobbed-by-students-during-visit-to-joint-security-area/ |archivedate=24 November 2009 }}</ref>

To continue to deter North Korean incursion, in 2014 the United States government exempted the Korean DMZ from its pledge to eliminate [[anti-personnel landmines]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/korearealtime/2014/09/24/why-the-korean-peninsula-keeps-landmines/ |title=Why the Korean Peninsula Keeps Land Mines |last=Kwaak |first=Jeyup S |publisher=Wall Street Journal |date=24 September 2014 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140924070350/https://blogs.wsj.com/korearealtime/2014/09/24/why-the-korean-peninsula-keeps-landmines/ |archivedate=24 September 2014 }}</ref> On October 1, 2018, however, a 20-day process began to remove landmines from both sides of the DMZ.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/10/01/north-south-korea-begin-removing-landmines-along-fortified-border/|title=North and South Korea begin removing landmines along fortified DMZ|last=Agency|first=Reuters News|date=2018-10-01|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2018-11-19|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>

==Joint Security Area==
[[Image:070401 Panmunjeom3.jpg|thumb|View of the North from the southern side of the [[Joint Security Area|JSA]]]]
[[Image:Joint Security Area from North Korea.jpg|thumb|Conference Row seen from the northern side of the [[Joint Security Area|JSA]]]]
{{main|Joint Security Area}}
Inside the DMZ, near the western coast of the peninsula, [[Panmunjom]] is the home of the Joint Security Area (JSA). Originally, it was the only connection between North and South Korea<ref>{{cite web|url=http://imcom.korea.army.mil/imakoroweb/sites/local/news/020808_IMCOMK_DMZ.asp |title=Panmunjon |publisher=army.mil.com |accessdate=2009-12-15 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090905081008/http://imcom.korea.army.mil/imakoroweb/sites/local/news/020808_IMCOMK_DMZ.asp |archivedate=5 September 2009 }}</ref> but that changed on 17 May 2007, when a [[Korail]] train went through the DMZ  to the North on the new [[Donghae Bukbu Line]] built on the east coast of Korea. However, the resurrection of this line was short-lived, as it closed again in July 2008 following an incident in which a South Korean tourist was shot and killed.

There are several buildings on both the north and the south side of the [[Military Demarcation Line]] (MDL), and there have been some built on top of it. The JSA is the location where all [[Inter-Korean summits|negotiations]] since 1953 have been held, including statements of Korean solidarity, which have generally amounted to little except a slight decline of [[Inter-Korean conflict|tensions]]. The MDL goes through the conference rooms and down the middle of the conference tables where the North Koreans and the United Nations Command (primarily South Koreans and Americans) meet face to face.

Within the JSA are a number of buildings for joint meetings called Conference Rooms. These are used for direct talks between the Korean War participants and parties to the armistice. Facing the Conference Row buildings are the North Korean ''[[Panmungak]]'' ({{lang-en|Panmun Hall}}) and the South Korean [[Freedom House (Joint Security Area)|Freedom House]]. In 1994, North Korea enlarged Panmungak by adding a third floor. In 1998, South Korea built a new Freedom House for its [[Red Cross]] staff and to possibly host reunions of families separated by the [[Korean War]]. The new building incorporated the old Freedom House Pagoda within its design.

Since 1953 there have been occasional confrontations and skirmishes within the JSA. The [[Korean axe murder incident|axe murder incident]] in August 1976 involved the attempted trimming of a tree which resulted in two deaths ([[Captain (United States O-3)|Captain]] Arthur Bonifas and [[First Lieutenant]] Mark Barrett). Another incident occurred on 23 November 1984, when a Soviet tourist named Vasily Matuzok (sometimes spelled Matusak), who was part of an official trip to the JSA (hosted by the North), ran across the MDL shouting that he wanted to [[defection|defect]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stripes.com/news/pacific/korea/general-revisits-deadly-1984-thanksgiving-firefight-at-dmz-1.161443 |title=General revisits deadly 1984 Thanksgiving firefight at DMZ |work=Stars and Stripes |accessdate=13 March 2016 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160309182210/http://www.stripes.com/news/pacific/korea/general-revisits-deadly-1984-thanksgiving-firefight-at-dmz-1.161443 |archivedate=9 March 2016 }}</ref> North Korean troops immediately chased after him, opening fire. Border guards on the South Korean side returned fire, eventually surrounding the North Koreans as they pursued Matusak. One South Korean and three North Korean soldiers were killed in the action, and Matusak was not captured.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/ops/dmz-list.htm |title=Korea Demilitarized Zone Incidents |date=2009-05-28 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100331152533/http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/ops/dmz-list.htm |archivedate=31 March 2010 }}</ref>

In late 2009, South Korean forces in conjunction with the [[United Nations Command]] began renovation of its three guard posts and two checkpoint buildings within the JSA compound. Construction was designed to enlarge and modernize the structures. Work was undertaken a year after North Korea finished replacing four JSA guard posts on its side of the MDL.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.stripes.com/article.asp?section=104&article=65534 |title=South Korea to revamp DMZ towers |publisher=''[[Stars and Stripes (newspaper)|Stars and Stripes]]'' |date=2009-10-22 |accessdate=2009-11-09 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091022163155/http://www.stripes.com/article.asp?section=104&article=65534 |archivedate=22 October 2009 }}</ref> On 15 October 2018, during the high-level talks in Panmunjom, military officials of the rank of [[colonel]] from the two Koreas and Burke Hamilton, Secretary of the [[United Nations Command, Military Armistice Commission, Korea|UNC Military Armistice Commission]], announced measures to reduce conventional military threats, such as creating buffer zones along their land and sea boundaries and a no-fly zone above the border, removing 11 front-line guard posts by December, and [[demining]] sections of the Demilitarized Zone.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.kait8.com/2018/10/15/koreas-hold-high-level-peace-talks|title=Koreas agree to break ground on inter-Korean railroad|last=TONG-HYUNG|first=KIM|date=|work=Kait8.com|access-date=2018-11-19|language=en-US}}</ref>

==Villages==
[[Image:Propagandavillage.JPG|thumb|North Korean [[Kijŏng-dong]], seen from South Korea]]
Both North and South Korea maintain ''peace villages'' in sight of each other's side of the DMZ. In the South, [[Daeseong-dong]] is administered under the terms of the DMZ. Villagers are classed as Republic of Korea citizens, but are [[Tax exemption|exempt]] from paying tax and other civic requirements such as [[Conscription in South Korea|military service]]. In the North, [[Kijŏng-dong]] features a number of brightly painted, poured-concrete multi-story buildings and apartments with electric lighting. These features represented an unheard-of level of luxury for rural Koreans, North or South, in the 1950s. The town was oriented so that the bright blue roofs and white sides of the buildings would be the most distinguishing features when viewed from the border. However, based on scrutiny with modern telescopic lenses, it has been claimed the buildings are mere concrete shells lacking window glass or even interior rooms,<ref name="potts">{{Cite journal|last=Potts|first=Rolf|date=1999-02-03|title=Korea's No-man's-land|url=http://www.salon.com/1999/02/03/feature_115/|deadurl=no|journal=[[Salon (magazine)|Salon]]|volume=|pages=|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130215050040/http://www.salon.com/1999/02/03/feature_115/|archivedate=15 February 2013|via=}}</ref><ref>O'Neill, Tom. "Korea's DMZ: Dangerous Divide". ''National Geographic'', July 2003.</ref> with the building lights turned on and off at set times and the empty sidewalks swept by a [[skeleton crew]] of [[Property caretaker|caretaker]]s in an effort to preserve the illusion of activity.<ref>Silpasornprasit, Susan. [http://imcom.korea.army.mil/imakoroweb/sites/local/news/020808_IMCOMK_DMZ.asp  "Day trip to the DMZ: A look inside the Korean Demilitarized Zone".] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090330022530/http://imcom.korea.army.mil/imakoroweb/sites/local/news/020808_IMCOMK_DMZ.asp |date=30 March 2009 }} IMCOM-Korea Region Public Affairs Office, US Army. Retrieved 2009-01-30.</ref>

===Flagpoles===
{{multiple image|image1=Daeseong-dong_Scene.jpg|caption1=South Korean [[Daeseong-dong]] and its flagpole|image2=Gijeong-ri Flag.jpg|caption2=The world's fourth-tallest flagpole (160m) flying a [[Flag of North Korea|North Korean flag]] over [[Kijong-dong|Kijŏng-dong]] near [[Panmunjom]]}}
In the 1980s, the South Korean government built a {{Convert|98.4|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} [[flagpole|flag pole]] in Daeseong-dong, which flies a [[flag of South Korea|South Korean flag]] weighing {{Convert|130|kg|lb|0|abbr=off}}. In what some have called the "flagpole war," the North Korean government responded by building the {{Convert|160|m|ft|0|abbr=on|sp=us}} [[Panmunjeom flagpole]] in Kijŏng-dong, only {{Convert|1.2|km|mi|1|abbr=on}} west of the border with South Korea. It flies a {{Convert|270|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}} [[flag of North Korea]]. As of 2014, the Panmunjom flagpole is the fourth tallest in the world, after the [[Jeddah Flagpole]] in [[Jeddah]], [[Saudi Arabia]], at {{Convert|170|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}, the [[Dushanbe Flagpole]] in [[Dushanbe]], [[Tajikistan]], at {{Convert|165|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} and the pole at the [[National Flag Square]] in [[Baku]], [[Azerbaijan]], which is {{Convert|162|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2002/WORLD/asiapcf/east/02/19/koreas.dmz/ |title=CNN.com – Korea's DMZ: 'Scariest place on Earth' |accessdate=2007-10-23 |date=2002-02-20 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012164210/http://edition.cnn.com/2002/WORLD/asiapcf/east/02/19/koreas.dmz/ |archivedate=12 October 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://economy.ohmynews.com/articleview/article_blogview.asp?at_code=370439 |script-title=ko:개성에 '구멍탄' 5만장 배달했습니다 |work=economy.ohmynews.com |accessdate=2006-12-06 |language=ko }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=Al83tito |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>

==DMZ-related incidents and incursions==
[[File:Members of 2nd Engineer Battalion begin to cut down the tree.jpg|thumb|[[Axe murder incident#Operation Paul Bunyan|Operation Paul Bunyan]], to remove a tree in front of the [[Bridge of No Return]], takes place following the [[axe murder incident]] in August 1976.]]
{{Main|List of border incidents involving North and South Korea}}
Since demarcation, the DMZ has had numerous cases of incidents and incursions by both sides, although the North Korean government typically never acknowledges direct responsibility for any of these incidents (there are exceptions, such as the axe incident).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fas.org/man/crs/RL30004.pdf |title=North Korea: Chronology of Provocations, 1950 – 2003 |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2012-02-02 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060905062431/http://www.fas.org/man/crs/RL30004.pdf |archivedate=5 September 2006 }}</ref> This was particularly intense during the [[Korean DMZ Conflict (1966–1969)]] when a series of skirmishes along the DMZ resulted in the deaths of 43 [[US soldier|American]], 299 [[South Korean soldier|South Korean]] and 397 [[North Korean army|North Korean soldiers]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Bolger|first=Daniel|title=Scenes from an Unfinished War: Low intensity conflict in Korea 1966–1969|publisher=Diane Publishing Co|isbn=978-0-7881-1208-9|year=1991}}</ref> This included the [[Blue House raid|Blue House Raid]] in 1968, an attempt to [[Assassination|assassinate]] President [[Park Chung-hee|Park Chung Hee]] at the [[Blue House]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cgsc.leavenworth.army.mil/carl/download/csipubs/scenes/scen_c3.pdf |title=Scenes from an Unfinished War: Low-Intensity Conflict in Korea, 1966–1968 |publisher=Cgsc.leavenworth.army.mil |date= |accessdate=2012-02-02 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090325103728/http://cgsc.leavenworth.army.mil/carl/download/csipubs/scenes/scen_c3.pdf |archivedate=25 March 2009 }}</ref>

In 1976, in now-[[Declassification|declassified]] meeting minutes, U.S. Deputy Secretary of Defense [[William Clements]] told Secretary of State [[Henry Kissinger]] that there had been 200 raids or incursions into North Korea from the south, though not by the U.S. military.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://history.state.gov/historicaldocuments/frus1969-76ve12/d286 |title=Minutes of Washington Special Actions Group Meeting, Washington, 25 August 1976, 10:30 a.m. |date=25 August 1976 |accessdate=12 May 2012 |publisher=[[Office of the Historian]], US Department of State |quote=Clements: I like it. It doesn't have an overt character. I have been told that there have been 200 other such operations and that none of these have surfaced. Kissinger: It is different for us with the War Powers Act. I don't remember any such operations. |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925121535/http://history.state.gov/historicaldocuments/frus1969-76ve12/d286 |archivedate=25 September 2012 }}</ref> Details of only a few of these incursions have become public, including raids by South Korean forces in 1967 that had sabotaged about 50 North Korean facilities.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2011/02/116_80936.html |title=S. Korea raided North with captured agents in 1967 |publisher=The Korea Times |author=Lee Tae-hoon |date=7 February 2011 |accessdate=12 May 2012 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121001195904/http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2011/02/116_80936.html |archivedate=1 October 2012 }}</ref>

===Incursion tunnels===
{{See also|Tunnel warfare}}
Since 15 November 1974, South Korea has discovered four tunnels crossing the DMZ that had been dug by North Korea. The orientation of the blasting lines within each tunnel indicated they were dug by North Korea. North Korea claimed that the tunnels were for [[coal mining]]; however, no coal was found in the tunnels, which were dug through granite. Some of the tunnel walls were painted black to give the appearance of [[anthracite]].<ref>{{cite book|first=Jim|last=Sides|title=Almost Home|publisher=Xulon Press|year=2009|isbn=978-1-60791-740-3|page=118}}</ref>

The tunnels are believed to have been planned as a military invasion route by North Korea. They run in a north-south direction and do not have branches. Following each discovery, engineering within the tunnels has become progressively more advanced. For example, the third tunnel sloped slightly upwards as it progressed southward, to prevent [[water stagnation]]. Today, visitors from the south may visit the second, third and fourth tunnels through guided tours.<ref>{{cite web|title=Demilitarized Zone |publisher=GlobalSecurity.org |url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/ops/dmz.htm |accessdate=2007-11-09 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071105034940/http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/ops/dmz.htm |archivedate=5 November 2007 }}</ref>

====First tunnel====
The first of the tunnels was discovered on 20 November 1974, by a South Korean Army patrol, noticing steam rising from the ground. The initial discovery was met with [[Automatic firearm|automatic fire]] from North Korean soldiers. Five days later, during a subsequent exploration of this tunnel, [[United States Navy|US Navy]] Commander Robert M. Ballinger and [[Republic of Korea Marine Corps|ROK Marine Corps]] Major Kim Hah-chul were killed in the tunnel by a North Korean explosive device. The blast also wounded five Americans and one South Korean from the United Nations Command.

The tunnel, which was about {{convert|3|by|4|ft|1|abbr=on|order=flip}}, extended more than {{convert|1|km|yd|abbr=on}} beyond the MDL into South Korea. The tunnel was reinforced with concrete slabs and had electric power and lighting. There were [[Weapon storage area|weapon storage]] and sleeping areas. A [[narrow-gauge railway]] with carts had also been installed. Estimates based on the tunnel's size suggest it would have allowed considerable numbers of soldiers to pass through it.<ref name=bermudez_js>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130621051225/http://www.korean-war.com/Archives/2002/02/msg00289.html |archivedate=2013-06-21 |url=http://www.korean-war.com/Archives/2002/02/msg00289.html |title=Tunnels under the DMZ |author=Bermudez, Joseph S. Jr |accessdate=2010-03-26 |website=korean-war.com}}</ref>

====Second tunnel====
[[File:Entrance to the 4th Infiltration Tunnel, Korean DMZ.jpg|thumb|Entrance to the North Korean-dug 4th Infiltration Tunnel, Korean DMZ]]
The second tunnel was discovered on 19 March 1975. It is of similar length to the first tunnel. It is located between {{convert|50|and|160|m|ft|abbr=on}} below ground, but is larger than the first, approximately {{convert|2|by|2|m|ft|0|sp=us|abbr=in}}.

====Third tunnel====
{{main|Third Tunnel of Aggression}}
The third tunnel was discovered on 17 October 1978. Unlike the previous two, the third tunnel was discovered following a tip from a [[North Korean defectors|North Korean defector]]. This tunnel is about {{convert|1600|m|ft|abbr=on}} long and about {{convert|73|m|ft|abbr=on}} below ground.<ref>{{cite book|last=Robinson|first=Martin|title=Seoul|year=2009|publisher=Lonely Planet|isbn=978-1-74104-774-5|pages=162}}</ref> Foreign visitors touring the South Korean DMZ may view inside this tunnel using a sloped access shaft.

====Fourth tunnel====
A fourth tunnel was discovered on 3 March 1990, north of [[Haean]] town in the former [[Punchbowl, Korea|Punchbowl]] battlefield. The tunnel's dimensions are {{convert|2|by|2|m|ft|0|sp=us|abbr=in}}, and it is {{convert|145|m|ft}} deep. The method of construction is almost identical in structure to the second and the third tunnels.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.panmunjomtour.com/english/dmz/dmz_20.htm |title=The Fourth Infiltration Tunnel |publisher=Panmunjom Travel Center |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070309084651/http://www.panmunjomtour.com/english/dmz/dmz_20.htm |archivedate= 9 March 2007 |df= }}</ref>

===Korean Wall===
[[File:The Korean Wall in the DMZ.JPG|thumb|The Korean Wall, or anti-tank barrier, in the [[demilitarized zone]] seen through binoculars from the North Korean side.]]
According to North Korea, between 1977 and 1979 the South Korean and United States authorities constructed a concrete wall along the DMZ.<ref name="tetteroo"/> North Korea, however, began to propagate information about the wall after the [[fall of the Berlin Wall]] in 1989, when the symbolism of a wall [[Injustice|unjustly]] dividing a people became more apparent.<ref>{{cite book|last=Salzinger|first=Caroline|translator-last=Lempinen|translator-first=Ulla|title=Terveisiä pahan akselilta: Arkea ja politiikkaa maailman suljetuimmissa valtioissa|year=2008|publisher=Atena|location=Jyväskylä|language=fi|isbn=978-951-796-521-7|page=40}}</ref>

Various organizations, such as the North Korean tour guide company Korea Konsult, claimed a wall was dividing Korea, saying that:

{{quote|In the area south of the Military Demarcation Line, which cuts across Korea at its waist, there is a concrete wall which ... stretches more than {{convert|240|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} from east to west, is {{convert|5|-|8|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} high, {{convert|10|-|19|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} thick at the bottom, and {{convert|3|-|7|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} wide in the upper part. It is set with wire entanglements and dotted with gun embrasures, look-outs and varieties of military establishments.<!-- not in citation: [...] the South Korean rulers built this wall over a period of many years from 1977.--><ref>{{cite web|title=DMZ: Demilitarized Zone|url=http://koreakonsult.net/Attraction_DMZ_eng.html|publisher=''Korea Konsult''|accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref>}}

In December 1999, Chu Chang-jun, [[China–North Korea relations|North Korea's ambassador to China]], repeated claims that a "wall" divided Korea. He said the south side of the wall is packed with soil, which permits access to the top of the wall and makes it effectively invisible from the south side. He also claimed that it served as a bridgehead for any northward [[invasion]].<ref name="Wall">{{cite web|url=http://www.korean-war.com/Archives/2000/12/msg00041.html |title=New York Times, 1999 |publisher=Korean-war.com |date= |accessdate=2012-02-02 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120308122740/http://www.korean-war.com/Archives/2000/12/msg00041.html |archivedate= 8 March 2012 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Tear Down the Korean Wall |url=http://www.kimsoft.com/1997/nk9912.htm |work= |publisher=DPRK UN Mission |date=1999-12-03 |accessdate=2007-10-29 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060329064336/http://www.kimsoft.com/1997/nk9912.htm |archivedate=29 March 2006 }}</ref>

The United States and South Korea deny the wall's existence, although they do claim there are [[Anti-tank obstacles|anti-tank barriers]] along some sections of the DMZ.<ref>{{cite news|last=Eckholm |first=Erik |date=December 8, 1999 |title=Where Most See Ramparts, North Korea Imagines a Wall |url=http://partners.nytimes.com/library/world/asia/120899nkorea-skorea.html |newspaper=The New York Times |access-date=May 26, 2016 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816222047/http://partners.nytimes.com/library/world/asia/120899nkorea-skorea.html |archivedate=16 August 2016 }}</ref>

In the [[RT (TV network)|RT]] documentary ''10 Days in North Korea'', the crew shot footage of a wall as seen from North Korea and described it as a "5 metre high wall stretching from east to west".<ref>{{cite web|title=10 Days in North Korea |url=http://rt.com/shows/documentary/203135-north-korea-kim-jongun/ |author=Ángela Gallardo Bernal |publisher=RT |accessdate=20 February 2017 |date=9 November 2014 |id=at 19:30 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222101514/https://www.rt.com/shows/documentary/203135-north-korea-kim-jongun/ |archivedate=22 December 2016 }}</ref> Dutch journalist and filmmaker [[Peter Tetteroo]] also shot footage of a barrier in 2001 which his North Korean guides said was the Korean Wall.<ref name="tetteroo">{{cite web|url=http://www.filmakers.com/index.php?a=filmDetail&filmID=1138 |title=Welcome to North Korea: A film by Peter Tetteroo for KRO Television |accessdate=2009-12-29 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711001620/http://www.filmakers.com/index.php?a=filmDetail&filmID=1138 |archivedate=11 July 2011 }}</ref>

A 2007 [[Reuters]] report revealed that there is no coast to coast wall located across the DMZ and that the pictures of a "wall" which have been used in North Korean propaganda have merely been pictures of concrete anti-tank barriers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-korea-north-wall/north-korea-asks-south-to-tear-down-imaginary-wall-idUSSEO20068620071231|title=North Korea asks South to tear down imaginary wall|first=Jon|last=Herskovitz|date=December 31, 2007|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=October 1, 2018}}</ref> While 800,000 landmines were being removed in 2018, it was shown that the [[Joint Security Area]] along the Korean border was guarded by standard [[barbed wire]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-45704909|title=Koreas Start Removing Border landmines|last=|first=|date=2018-10-01|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-11-19|language=en-GB}}</ref>

==North Korean side of the DMZ==
[[Image:Entrance_of_Joint_Security_Area,_Korean_Demilitarized_Zone,_DPRK_side.jpg|thumb|DMZ, North Korea. [[Electric fence]]s are used in the Korean Demilitarized Zone as a means to seal off North Korea from South Korea. Behind the fence, there is a strip which has [[land mine]]s hidden beneath it.]]
The North Korean side of the DMZ primarily serves to defend North Korea from invasion by South Korean forces. It also serves a similar function as the [[Berlin Wall]] and the [[inner German border]] did against its own citizens in the former [[East Germany]] in that it stops North Korean citizens from defecting to South Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qsl.net/ah6hy/SKDMZ.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-03-12 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160914011727/http://www.qsl.net/ah6hy/SKDMZ.html |archivedate=14 September 2016 }} Bottom of the page. Retrieved 11 March 2017</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/05/20/world/north-korea-blocks-defections-across-dmz.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-03-12 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312202845/http://www.nytimes.com/1982/05/20/world/north-korea-blocks-defections-across-dmz.html |archivedate=12 March 2017 }} Retrieved 11 March 2017</ref>

From the armistice until 1972, approximately 7,700 South Korean soldiers and agents infiltrated North Korea to sabotage military bases and industrial areas.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/02/15/world/south-korean-movie-unlocks-door-on-a-once-secret-past.html?_r=0|title=South Korean Movie Unlocks Door on a Once-Secret Past|publisher=The New York Times|author=Norimitsu Onishi|date=15 February 2014|accessdate=13 March 2017}}</ref>

North Korea has thousands of artillery pieces near the DMZ. According to a 2018 article in ''[[The Economist]]'', North Korea could bombard Seoul with over 10,000 rounds every minute.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.economist.com/news/leaders/21735586-how-shifts-technology-and-geopolitics-are-renewing-threat-growing-danger|title=The Growing Danger of Great-Power Conflict|last=|first=|date=|website=The Economist|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-02-05}}</ref> Experts believe that 60 percent of its total [[artillery]] is positioned within a few kilometers of the DMZ acting as a deterrent against any South Korean invasion.

==Propaganda==
{{See also|Propaganda|Psychological warfare}}

===Loudspeaker installations===
From 1953 until 2004 both sides broadcast audio propaganda across the DMZ.<ref name=bbc-20040615/> Massive loudspeakers mounted on several of the buildings delivered DPRK propaganda broadcasts directed towards the south as well as propaganda radio broadcasts across the border.<ref name="potts"/> In 2004, the North and South agreed to end the broadcasts.<ref name="bbc-20040615">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/3807409.stm|title=Koreas Switch off Loudspeakers|last=|first=|date=15 June 2004|work=|accessdate=7 May 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040615123223/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/3807409.stm|archivedate=15 June 2004|deadurl=no|publisher=BBC}}</ref>

In August 2015, a [[Border Incident|border incident]] occurred where two South Korean soldiers were wounded after stepping on landmines that had allegedly been laid on the southern side of the DMZ by North Korean forces near an ROK guard post.<ref name="Choe Sang-hun">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/11/world/asia/north-korea-placed-mines-that-maimed-2-south-korean-soldiers-at-dmz-seoul-says.html?_r=0 |title=South Korea Accuses the North After Land Mines Maim Two Soldiers in DMZ |author=Choe Sang-hun |publisher=New York Times |date=10 August 2015 |accessdate=13 August 2015 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150813125328/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/11/world/asia/north-korea-placed-mines-that-maimed-2-south-korean-soldiers-at-dmz-seoul-says.html?_r=0 |archivedate=13 August 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Park |first=Ju-Min |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/08/10/us-southkorea-northkorea-mines-idUSKCN0QF07A20150810 |title=South Korea condemns North over land mine blast, vows retaliation |location=Seoul |publisher=[[Reuters]] |date=2015-08-10 |accessdate=2015-08-10 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150810235643/http://www.reuters.com/article/2015/08/10/us-southkorea-northkorea-mines-idUSKCN0QF07A20150810 |archivedate=10 August 2015 }}</ref> Both North Korea and South Korea then resumed broadcasting propaganda by loudspeaker.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/21/world/asia/north-korea-and-south-korea-exchange-rocket-and-artillery-fire.html |title=North Korea and South Korea Trade Fire Across Border, Seoul Says |date=21 August 2015 |work=The New York Times |accessdate=13 March 2016 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160117145801/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/21/world/asia/north-korea-and-south-korea-exchange-rocket-and-artillery-fire.html |archivedate=17 January 2016 }}</ref>  After four days of negotiations, on August 25, 2015 South Korea agreed to discontinue the broadcasts following a statement from North Korea's government expressing "regret" for the landmine incident.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bostonherald.com/news_opinion/international/asia/2015/08/south_korea_turns_off_propaganda_as_koreas_reach_deal |title=South Korea turns off propaganda as Koreas reach deal |date=2015-08-25 |accessdate=2015-08-25 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924004726/http://www.bostonherald.com/news_opinion/international/asia/2015/08/south_korea_turns_off_propaganda_as_koreas_reach_deal |archivedate=24 September 2015 }}</ref>

On 8 January 2016, in response to North Korea's supposed successful testing of a [[Thermonuclear weapon|hydrogen bomb]], South Korea resumed broadcasts directed at the north.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kim |first1=Sam |title=South Korea Punishes Kim Jong Un With K-Pop for Nuclear Test |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-01-07/south-korea-to-inflict-k-pop-blasts-on-kim-jong-un-for-nuke-test |accessdate=8 January 2016 |work=Bloomsberg |date=2016-01-07 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107213804/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-01-07/south-korea-to-inflict-k-pop-blasts-on-kim-jong-un-for-nuke-test |archivedate=7 January 2016 }}</ref>  On 15 April 2016, it was reported that the South Koreans purchased a new stereo system to combat the North's broadcasts.<ref name=thereg-20160415>{{cite news|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2016/04/15/south_korea_to_upgrade_national_stereo_system_at_cost_of_us16m/ |title=South Korea to upgrade national stereo defence system for US$16m |author=Simon Sharwood |newspaper=The Register |date=15 April 2016 |accessdate=22 April 2016 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160419011741/http://www.theregister.co.uk/2016/04/15/south_korea_to_upgrade_national_stereo_system_at_cost_of_us16m/ |archivedate=19 April 2016 }}</ref>

===Balloons===
{{main|Balloon propaganda campaigns in Korea}}
Both North and South Korea have held [[Airborne leaflet propaganda|balloon propaganda leaflet]] campaigns since the Korean War.{{sfn|Jung|2014|p=16}}

In recent years, mainly South Korean [[non-governmental organization]]s have been involved in launching balloons targeted at the DMZ and beyond.{{sfn|Jung|2014|p=9}} Due to the winds, the balloons tend to fall near the DMZ where there are mostly [[North Korean soldier|North Korean soldiers]] to see the leaflets.<ref name="Higginbotham2014">{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/bw/articles/2014-06-05/the-no-tech-tactics-of-north-koreas-target-zero-park-sang-hak#p4 |title=The No-Tech Tactics of North Korea's Most Wanted Defector |last=Higginbotham |first=Adam |date=5 June 2014 |website=[[Bloomberg News]] |access-date=1 July 2015 |page=4 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150703211625/http://www.bloomberg.com/bw/articles/2014-06-05/the-no-tech-tactics-of-north-koreas-target-zero-park-sang-hak |archivedate=3 July 2015 }}</ref> As with the loudspeakers, balloon operations were mutually agreed to be halted between 2004 and 2010.{{sfn|Jung|2014|p=23}} It has been assessed that the activists' balloons may contribute to the decay of remaining cooperation between the Korean governments,<ref name="Feffer2014">{{cite web |url=http://www.ips-dc.org/koreas-balloon-war/ |title=Korea's Balloon War |last=Feffer |first=John |date=6 November 2014 |website=[[Institute for Policy Studies]] |publisher= |access-date=29 June 2015}}</ref> and the DMZ has become more [[Militarization|militarized]] in recent years.{{sfn|Jung|2014|p=31}}

Many North Korean leaflets during the [[Cold War]] gave instructions and maps to help targeted South Korean soldiers in defecting. One of the leaflets found on the DMZ included a map of [[Cho Dae-hum]]'s route of [[South Korean defectors|defection to North Korea]] across the DMZ. In addition to using balloons as a means of delivery, North Koreans have also used [[Rocket|rockets]] to send leaflets to the DMZ.<ref name="Friedman2006">{{cite web|url=http://www.psywarrior.com/NKoreaH.html |title=Communist Korean War Leaflets |last=Friedman |first=Herbert A. |date=5 January 2006 |website=www.psywarrior.com |publisher= |access-date=28 June 2015 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150711121501/http://www.psywarrior.com/NKoreaH.html |archivedate=11 July 2015 }}</ref>

===Dismantling of Border Propaganda===
On April 23, 2018, both North and South Korea officially cancelled their border propaganda broadcasts for the last time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/04/23/asia/north-korea-south-korea-upcoming-summit-intl/index.html|title=South Korea stops blasting propaganda along DMZ as summit looms|last=CNN|first=Joshua Berlinger and Yoonjung Seo,|work=CNN|access-date=2018-11-19}}</ref>  On May 1, 2018, the loudspeakers across the Korean border were dismantled.<ref name=may1>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2018/05/01/607399907/north-and-south-korea-dismantle-loudspeakers-blaring-propaganda-on-the-dmz |title=North And South Korea Dismantle Loudspeakers Blaring Propaganda On The DMZ : The Two-Way |publisher=NPR |date=2018-05-01 |accessdate=2018-10-01}}</ref> Also on May 1, both sides committed to ending the balloon campaigns.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pri.org/stories/2018-05-05/south-korea-faces-decision-over-leaflets-ties-warm-north|title=South Korea faces a decision over leaflets as ties warm with the North|last=|first=|date=|work=Public Radio International|access-date=2018-11-19|language=en-US}}</ref> On May 5, 2018, an attempt by North Korean defectors to disperse more balloon propaganda across the border from South Korea was halted by the South Korean government.<ref>https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/05/05/south-korea-sabotages-anti-north-korea-leaflet-drop/</ref> The no-fly zone which was established on November 1, 2018 also designated a no-fly zone for all aircraft types above the MDL, and prohibits hot-air balloons from traveling within 25 km of the Korean border's [[Military Demarcation Line]] (MDL).<ref name="nov1effect">[https://www.ncnk.org/sites/default/files/Agreement%20on%20the%20Implementation%20of%20the%20Historic%20Panmunjom%20Declaration%20in%20the%20Military%20Domain.pdf Agreement on the Implementation of the Historic Panmunjom Declaration in the Military Domain] , 2018 (PDF)</ref>

==Civilian Control Line==
{{multiple image
|total_width=478
|image1=Civilian_Control_Line,_Imjingak,_Paju,_South_Korea_(3162648972).jpg
|caption1=Civilian Control Line, Imjingak, Paju, South Korea
|image2=Korea_Civilian_Control_Line2010(1).JPG
|caption2=Civilian Control Line, South Korea
}}
The Civilian Control Line is a line that designates an additional buffer zone to the DMZ within a distance of {{Convert|5|to|20|km|lk=|abbr=on}} from the Southern Limit Line of the DMZ. Its purpose is to limit and control the entrance of civilians into the area in order to protect and maintain the security of military facilities and operations near the DMZ. The commander of the [[Eighth United States Army|8th US Army]] ordered the creation of the CCL and it was activated and first became effective in February 1954.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tourdmz.com/english/02dmz/p2-1.php |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-03-11 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170225025507/http://www.tourdmz.com/english/02dmz/p2-1.php |archivedate=25 February 2017 }} Retrieved 10 March 2017</ref>

The buffer zone that falls south of the Southern Limit Line is called the Civilian Control Zone. Barbed wire fences and manned military [[Guardpost|guard posts]] mark the Civilian Control Line. The Civilian Control Zone is necessary for the military to monitor civilian travel to tourist destinations close to the Southern Limit Line of the DMZ like the discovered infiltration tunnels and tourist observatories. Usually when traveling within the Civilian Control Zone, South Korean soldiers accompany tourist buses and cars as armed guards to monitor the civilians as well as to protect them from North Korean intruders.

Right after the [[Korean Armistice Agreement|ceasefire]], the Civilian Control Zone outside the DMZ encompassed 100 or so empty villages. The government implemented migration measures to attract settlers into the area. As a result, in 1983, when the area delineated by the Civilian Control Line was at its largest, a total of 39,725 residents in 8,799 households were living in the 81 villages located within the Civilian Control Zone.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.koreana.or.kr/user/0003/nd6245.do?View&boardNo=00000415&pubLang=English&pubYear=2016&pubMonth=AUTUMN&zineInfoNo=0003|title=Kor|last=|first=|date=|website=Koreana: Korean culture & arts|language=ko|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-03-17}}</ref>{{Dead link|date=November 2018}}

Most of the tourist and media photos of the "DMZ fence" are actually photos of the CCL fence. The actual DMZ fence on the Southern Limit Line is completely [[Limited-access road|off-limits]] to everybody except soldiers and it is illegal to take pictures of the DMZ fence. The CCL fence acts more as a deterrent for South Korean civilians from getting too close to the dangerous DMZ and is also the final barrier for North Korean [[Infiltration tactics|infiltrators]] if they get past the Southern Limit Line DMZ fence.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.researchgate.net/figure/277646914_fig1_Figure-1-A-map-of-the-study-site-presenting-the-location-of-Military-Demarcation |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-03-11 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312055444/https://www.researchgate.net/figure/277646914_fig1_Figure-1-A-map-of-the-study-site-presenting-the-location-of-Military-Demarcation |archivedate=12 March 2017 }} / up-close map of CCL/CCZ/Southern Limit Line. Retrieved 10 March 2017</ref>

==Neutral Zone of the Han River Estuary==
The whole estuary of the [[Han River (Korea)|Han River]] is deemed a "Neutral Zone" and is off-limits to all civilian vessels and is treated like the rest of the DMZ. Only [[Military vessel|military vessels]] are allowed within this neutral zone.

According to the July 1953 [[Korean Armistice Agreement]] civil [[Freight transport|shipping]] was supposed to be permissible in the Han River estuary and allow Seoul to be connected to the [[Yellow Sea]] (West Sea) via the Han River.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.findlaw.com/cnn/docs/korea/kwarmagr072753.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-04-14 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140305164517/http://news.findlaw.com/cnn/docs/korea/kwarmagr072753.html |archivedate=5 March 2014 }} Article 1, Section 5. Retrieved 11 March 2017</ref> However, both Koreas and the UNC failed to make this happen. The South Korean government ordered the construction of the [[Ara Canal]] to finally connect [[Seoul]] to the Yellow Sea, which was completed in 2012. Seoul was effectively landlocked from the ocean until 2012. The biggest limitation of the Ara Canal is it is too narrow to handle any vessels except small tourist boats and recreational boats, so Seoul still cannot receive large commercial ships or passenger ships in its port.

In recent years [[China|Chinese]] fishing vessels have taken advantage of the tense situation in the [[Han River (Korea)|Han River]] Estuary Neutral Zone and illegally fished in this area due to both the [[Korean People's Navy|North Korean]] and [[Republic of Korea Navy|South Korean]] navies never patrolling this area due to the fear of naval battles breaking out. This has led to [[Naval combat|firefights]] and sinkings of boats between Chinese fishermen and the [[South Korean Coast Guard]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maritime-executive.com/article/south-korea-to-respond-to-illegal-fishing-with-force |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-03-11 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312070836/http://www.maritime-executive.com/article/south-korea-to-respond-to-illegal-fishing-with-force |archivedate=12 March 2017 }} Retrieved 11 March 2017</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fiskerforum.dk/en/news/b/han-river-crackdown |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-03-11 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312060747/http://www.fiskerforum.dk/en/news/b/han-river-crackdown |archivedate=12 March 2017 }} Retrieved 11 March 2017</ref>

==Castle of Gung Ye==
Within the DMZ itself, in the town of [[Cheorwon]], is the old capital of the kingdom of [[Taebong]] (901–918), a regional upstart that became [[Goryeo]], the dynasty that ruled a [[History of Korea|united Korea]] from 918 to 1392.

[[Taebong]] was founded by the charismatic leader [[Gung Ye]], a brilliant if tyrannical one-eyed ex-[[Buddhist monk]]. Rebelling against the kingdom of [[Silla]], Korea's then ruling dynasty, he proclaimed the kingdom of [[Taebong]]—also called Later Goguryeo, in reference to the ancient kingdom of [[Goguryeo]] (37BCE-668CE)—in 901, with himself as king. The kingdom consisted of much of central Korea, including areas around the DMZ. He placed his capital in [[Cheorwon]], a mountainous region that was easily defensible (in the Korean War, this same region would earn the name "the [[Iron Triangle (Korea)|Iron Triangle]]").

As a former Buddhist monk, [[Gung Ye]] actively promoted the religion of [[Buddhism]] and incorporated Buddhist ceremonies into the new kingdom. Even after Gung Ye was [[Dethroning|dethroned]] by his own generals and replaced by [[Wang Geon]], the man who would rule over a united Korea as the first king of [[Goryeo]], this Buddhist influence would continue, playing a major role in shaping the culture of medieval Korea.

As the ruins of Gung Ye's capital lie in the DMZ itself, visitors cannot see them. Moreover, excavation work and research have been hampered by political realities. In the future, inter-Korean peace may allow for proper archaeological studies to be conducted on the castle site and other historical sites within and underneath the DMZ.<ref>Koehler, Rober. (2011). {{Google books|8FatCQAAQBAJ|''The DMZ: Dividing the Two Koreas''|page=108}}</ref>

The ruins of the capital city of Taebong, the ruins of the castle of Gung Ye, and King Gung Ye's [[tomb]] all lie within the DMZ and are off-limits to everybody except soldiers who patrol the DMZ.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://leekihwan.khan.kr/368 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-03-11 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312060535/http://leekihwan.khan.kr/368 |archivedate=12 March 2017 }} Retrieved 10 March 2017. Many pictures, maps, and description of the old Taebong capital that is stuck in the middle of the DMZ.</ref>

==Transportation==
[[Image:Donghae-bukbu line on Korean DMZ.JPG|thumb|The Donghae Bukbu Line on Korea's east coast. The road and rail link was built for South Koreans visiting the [[Mount Kumgang Tourist Region]] in the North.]]
[[File:DMZ train Seoul to Dorasan.jpg|thumb|[[DMZ Train]] tour organized by Korail]]
[[Panmunjeom]] is the site of the negotiations that ended the Korean War and is the main center of human activity in the DMZ.  The village is located on the main highway and near a railroad connecting the two Koreas.

The railway, which connects Seoul and [[Pyongyang]], was called the [[Gyeongui Line]] before division in the 1940s.  Currently the South uses the original name, but the North refers to the route as the P'yŏngbu Line. The railway line has been mainly used to carry materials and South Korean workers to the [[Kaesong Industrial Region]]. Its reconnection has been seen as part of the general improvement in the relations between North and South in the early part of this century. However, in November 2008 North Korean authorities closed the railway amid growing tensions with the South.<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://news.scotsman.com/northkorea/Last-train-to-Kaesong-as.4744792.jp|title=Last train to Kaesong as Korean relations cool|date=2008-11-28|publisher=News.Scotman.Com|location=Edinburgh|first=Jae-Soon|last=Chang}}</ref> Following the death of former [[President of South Korea|South Korean President]] [[Kim Dae-jung]], conciliatory talks were held between South Korean officials and a North Korean delegation who attended Kim's funeral. In September 2009, the Kaesong rail and road crossing was reopened.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.hani.co.kr/arti/english_edition/e_northkorea/375550.html |title=Inter-Korean economic cooperation Kaesong office reopens |publisher=Englishhani |date=2009-09-07 |accessdate=2009-09-17 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722143648/http://english.hani.co.kr/arti/english_edition/e_northkorea/375550.html |archivedate=22 July 2011 }}</ref>

The road at Panmunjeom, which was known historically as ''Highway One'' in the South, was originally the only access point between the two countries on the Korean Peninsula. Passage is comparable to the strict movements that occurred at [[Checkpoint Charlie]] in Berlin at the height of the [[Cold War]]. Both North and South Korea's roads end in the JSA; the highways do not quite join as there is a {{convert|20|cm|in|0|abbr=on}} concrete line that divides the entire site. People given the rare permission to cross this border must do so on foot before continuing their journey by road.

In 2007, on the east coast of Korea, the first train crossed the DMZ on the new [[Donghae Bukbu Line|Donghae Bukbu (Tonghae Pukpu) Line]]. The new rail crossing was built adjacent to the road which took South Koreans to [[Mount Kumgang Tourist Region]], a region of significant cultural importance for all Koreans. More than one million civilian visitors crossed the DMZ until the route was closed following the shooting of a 53-year-old South Korean tourist in July 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/world/2008-07/12/content_6839889.htm |title=ROK woman tourist shot dead at DPRK resort |publisher=''[[China Daily]]'' |date=2008-07-12 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120217140840/http://www2.chinadaily.com.cn/world/2008-07/12/content_6839889.htm |archivedate=17 February 2012 }}</ref> After a [[Joint investigation team|joint investigation]] was rebuffed by North Korea, the South Korean government suspended tours to the resort. Since then the resort and the Donghae Bukbu Line have effectively been closed by North Korea.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/7539368.stm |title=N Korea steps up row with South |publisher=BBC |date=2008-08-03 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090930093913/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/7539368.stm |archivedate=30 September 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/8639065.stm |title=North Korea 'to seize property at Kumgang resort' |publisher=BBC |date=2010-04-23}}</ref> Currently, the South Korean [[Korea Railroad Corporation]] (Korail) organizes tours to DMZ with special DMZ themed trains.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.letskorail.com/ebizbf/EbizBfAboutDmz_Train.do|title=Korail|website=www.letskorail.com}}</ref> 

On October 14, 2018, North and South Korea, agreed to meet the summit's goal of restoring railway and road transportation which had been cut since the Korean War by either late November or early December 2018.<ref>https://www.reuters.com/article/us-northkorea-southkorea/koreas-to-reconnect-roads-rail-u-s-concerned-over-easing-sanctions-idUSKCN1MP0D0</ref> Road and railway transportation along the DMZ was reconnected in November 2018.<ref name=nov22kr /><ref name=nov22 /><ref name=nov30 />

==Nature reserve==
In the past half century, the Korean DMZ has been a deadly place for humans, making habitation impossible. Only around the village of [[Panmunjom]] and more recently the Donghae Bukbu Line on Korea's east coast have there been regular incursions by people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2012/apr/13/wildlife-thriving-korean-demilitarised-zone |title=How wildlife is thriving in the Korean peninsula's demilitarised zone |first=Lisa |last=Brady |date=13 April 2012 |publisher= |via=The Guardian |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160905181630/https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2012/apr/13/wildlife-thriving-korean-demilitarised-zone |archivedate=5 September 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www1.american.edu/TED/ice/DMZ.HTM |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-09-01 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160520080629/http://www1.american.edu/TED/ice/DMZ.HTM |archivedate=20 May 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

This natural isolation along the {{convert|250|km|abbr=on}} length of the DMZ has created an [[involuntary park]] which is now recognized as one of the most well-preserved areas of temperate [[habitat]] in the world.<ref name="Green"/> In 1966 it was first proposed that the DMZ be turned into a [[national park]].<ref name="Paige 1967"/>

Several [[Endangered species|endangered animal and plant species]] now exist among the heavily fortified fences, [[landmines]] and listening posts. These include the endangered [[red-crowned crane]] (a staple of Asian art), the [[white-naped crane]], and, potentially, the extremely rare [[Siberian tiger]],<ref name="Green">{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2003/WORLD/asiapcf/east/08/22/korea.bio.dmz/ |title=Korea's DMZ: The thin green line |publisher=CNN |accessdate=2009-07-30 |date=2003-08-22 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090805110227/http://edition.cnn.com/2003/WORLD/asiapcf/east/08/22/korea.bio.dmz/ |archivedate=5 August 2009 }}</ref> [[Amur leopard]], and [[Asiatic black bear]]. [[Ecologist]]s have identified some 2,900 plant species, 70 types of mammals and 320 kinds of birds within the narrow buffer zone.<ref name="Green"/> Additional surveys are now being conducted throughout the region.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.ohmynews.com/articleview/article_view.asp?menu=c10400&no=199457&rel_no=1 |title=Korean 'Tigerman' Prowls the DMZ |publisher=International Korean News |accessdate=2009-07-17 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090813200543/http://english.ohmynews.com/articleview/article_view.asp?menu=c10400&no=199457&rel_no=1 |archivedate=13 August 2009 }}</ref>

The DMZ owes its varied [[biodiversity]] to its geography, which crosses mountains, prairies, swamps, lakes, and tidal marshes. [[Environmentalist|Environmentalists]] hope that the DMZ will be conserved as a [[nature reserve|wildlife refuge]], with a well-developed set of objective and management plans vetted and in place. In 2005, [[CNN]] founder and [[media mogul]] [[Ted Turner]], on a visit to North Korea, said that he would financially support any plans to turn the DMZ into a peace park and a UN-protected [[World Heritage Site]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/2005-11-18-turnerdmz_x.htm |title=Ted Turner: Turn Korean DMZ into peace park |publisher=USA TODAY |date=2005-11-18 |accessdate=2010-05-07 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091206190920/http://www.usatoday.com/news/world/2005-11-18-turnerdmz_x.htm |archivedate=6 December 2009 }}</ref>

In September 2011, South Korea submitted a nomination form to [[Man and the Biosphere Programme]] (MAB) in [[UNESCO]] for designation of {{convert|435|km²|sqmi|abbr=on}} in the southern part of the DMZ below the Military Demarcation Line, as well as {{convert|2979|km²|sqmi|abbr=on}} in privately controlled areas, as a Biosphere Reserve according to the Statutory Framework of the World Network of Biosphere Reserves.<ref name="Nomination of Korea DMZ Biosphere Reserve">{{cite web|last=Choi |first=Chungil |title=Nomination of Korea DMZ Biosphere Reserve |url=ftp://ftp.unesco.org/upload/sc/Advisory_Cttee2012/New%20BRs/Korea/DMZ/Letter%20of%20endorsement-DMZ.pdf |accessdate=3 October 2012 }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=Al83tito |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>  The MAB National Committee of the Republic of Korea mentioned only the southern part of DMZ to be nominated since there was no response from [[Pyongyang]] when it requested Pyongyang to push jointly. North Korea is a member nation of the international coordinating council of UNESCO's Man and the Biosphere Programme, which designates Biosphere Reserves.<ref name="Seoul to seek UNESCO Biosphere Reserve status for DMZ">{{cite news|last=Kim |first=Jeong-su |title=Seoul to seek UNESCO Biosphere Reserve status for DMZ |url=http://www.hani.co.kr/arti/english_edition/e_international/540913.html |accessdate=3 October 2012 |newspaper=Hankyoreh |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120722081415/http://www.hani.co.kr/arti/english_edition/e_international/540913.html |archivedate=22 July 2012 }}</ref>

North Korea opposed the application as a violation of the armistice agreement during the council's meeting in Paris on July 9 to 13, 2011. The South Korean government's attempt to designate the Demilitarized Zone (DMZ) a UNESCO Biosphere Reserve was turned down at UNESCO's MAB council meeting in Paris in July 2012. Pyongyang expressed its opposition by sending letters to 32 council member countries, except for South Korea, and the UNESCO headquarters a month prior to the meeting. At the council meeting, Pyongyang said the designation violated the Armistice Agreement.<ref name="Biosphere reserve status for the DMZ is urgent">{{cite news|last=Cho |first=Do-soon |title=Biosphere reserve status for the DMZ is urgent |url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joinsmsn.com/news/article/Article.aspx?aid=2957816 |accessdate=3 October 2012 |newspaper=JoonAng Daily |date=14 August 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130621051310/http://koreajoongangdaily.joinsmsn.com/news/article/Article.aspx?aid=2957816 |archivedate=21 June 2013 }}</ref>

==Destruction of Guard Posts==
On October 26, 2018, South Korean Major Gen. Kim Do-gyun and North Korean general Lt. Gen. An Ik San met in [[Tongilgak]] (the "Unification Pavilion"), a North Korean building located within the DMZ's Joint Security Area (JSA). There, they begun implementing new protocols which aim to reduce tension by requiring both North and South Korea to destroy 22 guard posts across the DMZ,<ref name="voaoct26">{{Cite news|url=https://www.voanews.com/a/koreas-continue-tension-easing-talks-as-the-north-criticizes-us/4630152.html|title=Koreas Continue Tension-Easing Talks as the North Criticizes US|last=Miller|first=Steve|work=VOA|access-date=2018-11-19|language=en}}</ref> among other steps. Both generals approved requirements for the guard posts to be destroyed by the end of November 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.apnews.com/9e3311a2c2a9431198032cdd6e7e86a2|title=2 Koreas to destroy 22 front-line guard posts by November|date=2018-10-26|work=AP NEWS|access-date=2018-11-19}}</ref> The JSA's guard posts were destroyed on October 25, 2018.<ref name=voaoct26 /><ref name="independentoct25">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theindependent.com/news/world/koreas-un-finish-withdrawing-firearms-from-border-village/image_55ab50f5-8704-5770-812d-87c7832e0568.html|title=2 Koreas to destroy 22 front-line guard posts by November|last=Jin-man|first=Lee|work=The Grand Island Independent|access-date=2018-11-19|language=en}}</ref><ref name="yonhapoct25">{{Cite news|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/news/2018/10/25/0200000000AEN20181025001351315.html|title=(LEAD) Two Koreas, UNC wrap up JSA disarmament|last=송상호|date=2018-10-25|work=Yonhap News Agency|access-date=2018-11-19|language=en}}</ref> North and South Korea agreed to dismantle 11 guard posts located within their individual country and deemed as "front-line."<ref name="etoct26">{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/defence/2-koreas-to-destroy-11-front-line-guard-posts-by-november/articleshow/66377151.cms|title=2 Koreas to destroy 11 front-line guard posts by November|date=2018-10-26|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2018-11-19}}</ref><ref name=reutersoct26 /><ref name=cgtnoct26 /> It was also agreed that after the posts are dismantled, both Koreas would also withdraw equipment and personnel stationed at each post as well.<ref name="reutersoct26">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-northkorea-southkorea/north-and-south-korea-agree-to-scrap-22-guard-posts-at-border-next-month-idUSKCN1N0082|title=North and South Korea agree to scrap 22 guard posts at border next...|last=Shin|first=Hyonhee|work=U.S.|access-date=2018-11-19|language=en-US}}</ref>  In tandem with the [[September 2018 inter-Korean summit#September 19 (Day 2)|September 2018 Pyongyang and Military Domain Agreements]],<ref name=reutersoct26 /><ref name=cgtnoct26 /><ref name=etoct26 /><ref>https://www.ncnk.org/sites/default/files/Agreement%20on%20the%20Implementation%20of%20the%20Historic%20Panmunjom%20Declaration%20in%20the%20Military%20Domain.pdf</ref> both sides also agreed to gradually remove all guard posts near the DMZ following verification in December 2018.<ref name="cgtnoct26">{{Cite news|url=https://news.cgtn.com/news/3d3d414e774d544d30457a6333566d54/share_p.html|title=Two Koreas agree to withdraw 11 guard posts in border area by late November|access-date=2018-11-19}}</ref><ref name=reutersoct26 /><ref name=etoct26 /> 

However, all remaining troops and equipment, including weapons, were withdrawn from all of the 22 "frontline" guard posts before destruction began and both Koreas later agreed to individually destroy 10 of these guard posts instead of 11.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asia/north-and-south-korea-begin-destroying-border-guard-posts-10919016|title=North and South Korea begin destroying border guard posts|work=Channel NewsAsia|access-date=2018-11-19|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=rappler11 /><ref name=latnov10 /><ref name=sfcnov10 />

On November 4, 2018, the North and South Korean governments hoisted a yellow flag above each of their 11 DMZ guard posts to publicly indicate that they all will be dismantled.<ref>http://english.hani.co.kr/arti/english_edition/e_northkorea/868900.html</ref><ref>http://english.hani.co.kr/arti/english_edition/e_northkorea/868900.html</ref> On November 10, 2018, the withdrawal of military personnel and weapons from all of the DMZ's 22 "front-line" guard posts was completed.<ref name="latnov10">{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/world/la-fg-korea-guard-post-withdrawals-20181110-story.html|title=In latest trust-building step, North and South Korean military finish withdrawal from front-line guard posts|last=Press|first=Associated|website=latimes.com|access-date=2018-11-19}}</ref><ref>http://www.hastingstribune.com/koreas-complete-the-disarming-of-guard-posts/article_bddc8489-3eb5-5982-b626-a4ed5d6e69dc.html</ref><ref name="sfcnov10">{{Cite news|url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/world/article/North-South-dismantle-22-guard-posts-along-border-13380901.php|title=North, South dismantle 22 guard posts along border|date=2018-11-10|work=SFChronicle.com|access-date=2018-11-19|language=en-US}}</ref> The destruction of 20 guard posts officially began on November 11, 2018.<ref name=nov11kh>http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20181111000255</ref><ref name=yonhapnov11>http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/news/2018/11/11/0200000000AEN20181111005200320.html</ref> However, both Koreas amended the original agreement and decided to preserve 2 of the 22 now demilitarized frontline guard posts.<ref name=nov11kh /><ref name=yonhapnov11 /> Both of the posts which were planned to be preserved are located on the opposite sides of the Korean border.<ref name="rappler11">{{Cite news|url=https://www.rappler.com/world/regions/asia-pacific/216465-north-south-korea-begin-destroying-border-guard-posts|title=North and South Korea begin destroying border guard posts|work=Rappler|access-date=2018-11-19|language=en}}</ref>

On November 15, 2018, destruction of two DMZ guard posts, one being located in South Korea and the other located in North Korea, was completed.<ref name=nov15>https://www.thestar.com/news/world/2018/11/15/south-korea-destroys-guard-posts-along-border-with-north-korea.html</ref><ref name=mtnov15>https://www.military.com/daily-news/2018/11/16/south-korea-dismantles-guard-posts-dynamite-excavators.html</ref> Work was still ongoing to complete the destruction of other guard posts as well.<ref name=nov15 /><ref name=mtnov15 /> On November 23, 2018, it was revealed that South Korea was slowly destroying their guard posts with [[excavator]]s.<ref name=khnov23 />

On November 20, 2018, North Korea, hoping to further ease tensions with South Korea, destroyed all of their 10 remaining "frontline" guard posts.<ref name=abc11>https://abc11.com/north-korea-detonates-dmz-guard-posts-at-southern-border/4726650/</ref><ref name=nov20>https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/seoul-north-korea-explodes-10-guard-posts-lower-59309949</ref> The South Korean Defense Ministry released photos confirming this and also released a statement stating that North Korea had informed them about the plans to demolish them before it took place.<ref name=nov20 /> This came in accordance with the earlier agreements.<ref name=abc11 /> South Korea also released videos of the guard posts being destroyed as well.<ref>https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/north-korea-video-south-korea-dmz-guard-posts-explode-peace-agreement-border-a8643876.html</ref>

On November 30, 2018, both Koreas completed work to dismantle 10 of their "frontline" guard posts.<ref name=belarusnov30 /><ref name=nov30 /> However, the later agreement for each Korea to preserve one "frontline" post was upheld as well.<ref name=nov30 /> The "frontline" guard post which was preserved on the North Korean side of the DMZ was visited by Kim Jong Un in 2013 when tensions were rising between both Koreas.<ref name=khnov23>http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20181120000703</ref>

==Establishment of Buffer Zones, No-Fly Zones and Yellow Sea Peace Zones==
On November 1, 2018, [[buffer zones]] were established across the DMZ by the North and South Korean militaries.<ref name=nov1 /> In compliance with the Comprehensive Military Agreement which was signed at the [[September 2018 inter-Korean summit]],<ref name=ncnkdirect /> the buffer zone helps ensure that both North and South Korea will effectively ban hostility on land, air, and sea.<ref name=nov1 /> Both Koreas are prohibited from conducting [[Live fire exercise|live-fire artillery drills]] and regiment-level field maneuvering exercises or those by bigger units within 5 kilometers of the Military Demarcation Line (MDL).<ref name="nov1">{{Cite news|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/news/2018/11/01/0200000000AEN20181101002500315.html|title=Koreas halt all 'hostile' military acts near border|last=이치동|date=2018-11-01|work=Yonhap News Agency|access-date=2018-11-19|language=en}}</ref> The buffer zones stretch from the north of Deokjeok Island to the south of Cho Island in the West Sea and the north of [[Sokcho]] city and south of Tongchon County in the East (Yellow) Sea.<ref name="ncnkdirect">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2018/10/two-koreas-end-military-drills-begin-operation-of-no-fly-zone-near-mdl-mnd/|title=Two Koreas end military drills, begin operation of no-fly zone near MDL: MND {{!}} NK News - North Korea News|date=2018-10-31|work=NK News - North Korea News|access-date=2018-11-19|language=en-US}}</ref>

[[No-fly zones]] have also been established along the DMZ to ban the operation of drones, helicopters and other aircraft over an area up to {{Convert|40|km||abbr=on}} away from the MDL.<ref name=nov1 /> For [[Unmanned aerial vehicle|UAVs]], within {{Convert|15|km||abbr=on}} from the MDL in the East and {{Convert|10|km||abbr=on}} from the MDL in the West.<ref name=nov1effect /> Hot-air balloons cannot travel within {{Convert|25|km||abbr=on}} of the DMZ as well.<ref name=nov1effect /> For fixed-wing aircraft, no fly zones are designated within {{Convert|40|km||abbr=on}} from the MDL in the East (between MDL Markers No. 0646 and 1292) and within {{Convert|20|km||abbr=on}} of the MDL in the West (between MDL Markers No. 0001 and 0646).<ref name=ncnkdirect /> For [[rotary-wing aircraft]], the no fly zones are designated within {{Convert|10|km||abbr=on}} of the MDL.<ref name=ncnkdirect /> 

Both Koreas also created "peace zones" near their [[Border dispute|disputed]] Yellow Sea border.<ref name=nov1 />

==Reconnecting of MDL-crossing road==
On November 22, 2018, North and South Korea completed construction to connect a three kilometer road along the DMZ, 90 km northeast of Seoul.<ref name=nov22kr>https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20181122006452315?section=national/defense</ref><ref name=nov22>https://www.aa.com.tr/en/politics/south-north-korea-connect-border-road-through-dmz/1318769</ref> This road, which crosses the Korean MDL land border, consists of 1.7 km in South Korea and 1.3 km in North Korea.<ref name=nov22 /> The road was reconnected for the first time in 14 years in an effort to assist with a process at the DMZ's Arrowhead Hill involving the removal of landmines and exhumation of Korean War remains.<ref>http://www.asianews.it/news-en/After-14-years,-a-road-to-unite-the-Koreas-and-recover-the-remains-of-the-fallen-45545.html</ref><ref>https://www.yahoo.com/news/north-south-korea-join-roads-124905264.html</ref><ref>https://www.cairnspost.com.au/news/national/north-and-south-korea-join-roads-after-14-years/video/af8a644187eb15024a900b16826ebd24</ref>

==Presence of landmines and Korean War remains==
On October 1, 2018, North and South Korean military engineers began a scheduled 20 day removal process of landmines and other explosives planted across the DMZ's [[Joint Security Area]] of the (DMZ).<ref>https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/10/01/north-south-korea-begin-removing-landmines-along-fortified-border/</ref><ref name=bbckoreaoct /><ref name=oct1>https://www.cbsnews.com/news/north-korea-south-korea-removing-land-mines-dmz-panmunjom-arrow-head-hill/</ref> Work to remove landmines from the Joint Security Area was completed on October 25, 2018.<ref>http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=3054494</ref><ref>https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/nation/2018/10/356_257291.html</ref><ref>https://pulsenews.co.kr/view.php?year=2018&no=653231</ref><ref name=bbckoreaoct>https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-45704909</ref> demining had begun at the DMZ's Arrowhead Hill and resulted in the discovery of Korean War remains.<ref name=oct25nov30>https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/south-korea-finds-war-remains-border-demining-58732705</ref><ref>https://www.dailyherald.com/article/20181025/news/310259972</ref> Work between both Koreas to remove landmines from Arrowhead Hill was completed on November 30, 2018.<ref name=nov30kr>https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20181130002400315</ref><ref name=belarusnov30>https://eng.belta.by/society/view/koreas-complete-work-on-removing-some-guard-posts-land-mines-in-dmz-116996-2018/</ref>

==Inter-Korean railroad services==
On November 30, 2018, following the removal of the "frontline" guard posts and Arrowhead Hill landmines, railroad services between North and South Korea which ceased in November 2008 resumed.<ref name=nov30>https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/11/30/first-train-decade-departs-south-korea-north-korea/</ref> The same day, 30 officials from both North and South Korea started an 18-day survey of a 400-kilometre (248-mile) railroad section in North Korea alongside the DMZ between Kaesong and Sinuiju.<ref name=voanov30>https://www.voanews.com/a/koreas-survey-railway-tracks-cut-since-the-korean-war/4681029.html</ref><ref>https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/nation/2018/11/356_259637.html</ref> Efforts to conduct the survey had previously been obstructed due to the presence of the guard posts and the Arrowhead Hill landmines.<ref name=nov30 /> The survey will then follow the groundbreaking of a new railroad along the DMZ.<ref>https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/nation/2018/11/356_259637.html</ref>

