{{Merge|Advance parole|date=August 2018}}
'''Parole''' in the [[Immigration and Nationality Act]] (INA) of the [[United States]] generally refers to any [[Alien_(law)#United_States|alien]] who is under the [[wikt:supervision#English|supervision]] of the [[United States Department of Homeland Security|U.S. Department of Homeland Security]] (DHS). Any alien who is inadmissible to the United States may apply for [[advance parole]] ([[Form I-131]]), which is also known as "humanitarian parole," and when granted allows the alien to stay in the country until the document expires.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uscis.gov/humanitarian/humanitarian-or-significant-public-benefit-parole-individuals-outside-united-states |title=Humanitarian or Significant Public Benefit Parole for Individuals Outside the United States |date=December 15, 2017 |accessdate=August 19, 2018}}</ref> Humanitarian parole is granted only in [[exceptional circumstances]] and on a case-by-case basis at the discretion of the DHS.<ref>''New York Times'': [https://www.nytimes.com/2005/10/14/nyregion/14orphan.html Nina Bernstein, "A Contest of Suffering, With the U.S. as a Prize," October 14, 2005], accessed August 7, 2011</ref>
==Parole for start-up entrepreneurs== The DHS has published a new rule, effective July 17, 2017, which adds new provisions regarding the use of parole on a case-by-case basis with respect to entrepreneurs of start-up entities who demonstrate that they will provide a significant public benefit to the United States.<ref>{{cite web|title=USCIS FINAL RULE ON PAROLE FOR START-UP ENTREPRENEURS|publisher=Givi Kutidze|date=January 15, 2017|url=http://www.us-counsel.com/rule-parole-start-entrepreneurs/}}</ref>
